====华语====
{{Main|新加坡华语|新加坡式华语}}

[[现代标准汉语|华语]]大致上是新加坡华族社会的通用语。<ref name="BBC">{{cite news |last=Oi |first=Mariko |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-11468401 |title=BBC News - Singapore's booming appetite to study Mandarin |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2010-10-05 |accessdate=2011-01-27 |archive-date=2021-03-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210307233129/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-11468401 |dead-url=no }}</ref>新加坡由英国殖民统治的1920年代，华语引进来到了新加坡，在新加坡以华语为教学媒介语的华校日渐增加。<ref name="countrystudies">{{cite web |url=http://countrystudies.us/singapore/20.htm |title=Singapore - Language |publisher=Countrystudies.us |date= |accessdate=2011-01-27 |archive-date=2010-11-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121051746/http://countrystudies.us/singapore/20.htm |dead-url=no }}</ref>

由于中国的经济崛起以及中国大量移民新加坡，华语在新加坡有所上升。<ref>Lee Kuan Yew, ''From Third World to First: The Singapore Story: 1965-2000'', HarperCollins, 2000. ISBN 0-06-019776-5.</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=english@peopledaily.com.cn |url=http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90001/90776/90883/6759455.html |title=Mandarin will become Singaporean mother tongue - People's Daily Online |publisher=English.peopledaily.com.cn |date= |accessdate=2011-01-27 |archive-date=2012-10-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015053131/http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90001/90776/90883/6759455.html |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.news.gov.sg/public/sgpc/en/media_releases/agencies/mica/speech/S-20090317-1/AttachmentPar/00/file/SMC%20Appendix%20-%20Dominant%20Home%20Language%20of%20Chinese%20Pri-one%20students.doc |title=Dominant Home Language of Chinese Primary One Students |publisher=Ministry of Education, Singapore |accessdate=2011-02-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226151824/http://www.news.gov.sg/public/sgpc/en/media_releases/agencies/mica/speech/S-20090317-1/AttachmentPar/00/file/SMC%20Appendix%20-%20Dominant%20Home%20Language%20of%20Chinese%20Pri-one%20students.doc |archivedate=2010-12-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asiaone.com/Business/SME%2BCentral/Talking%2Bpoint/Story/A1Story20090916-168233.html |title=Eyeing China, Singapore sees Mandarin as its future |publisher=Asiaone.com |date=2009-09-16 |accessdate=2011-01-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104163230/http://www.asiaone.com/Business/SME%2BCentral/Talking%2Bpoint/Story/A1Story20090916-168233.html |archive-date=2010-11-04 |dead-url=yes }}</ref><ref name="BBC"/>

